column168: On 10/1/2011 at 0239 hours, personnel in the CSXT Stanley yard discovered PROX 33585, a residue tank car of Isobutylene, hissing from the top of the tank car. On October 3, 2011 at 1837 hours, personnel at the CSXT Russell yard in Russell, KY discovered NDYX 113556, a loaded tank car of Sulfur, Molten, emitting a vapor with a small amount of product atop of the tank car. The tank car was isolated and the shipper, SG Solutions, was notified via CHEMTREC report  2011-10-03-00245. While loading a drum of hazardous waste onto the rear of a truck, the forklift hit a bump causing the drum to fall from the pallet on which it was being transported onto the ground.  The top ring of the drum hit the ground, bending it and causing liquid to leak out.  The drum was immediately righted.  The driver and loader donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and overpacked the drum into a suitable salvage drum.  The spill was cleaned up with an absorbent material which was also placed into the salvage drum.  The drum was then loaded onto the truck with no further incidents.
column169: The forklift operator should have used better caution and care in loading the drum in this manner.  His employer was notified of the incident.

The three piece loading valve assembly seperated under 20 psig and sprayed an aerosol of HCL into the spill dam area of a FRP Tank Trailer. Pressure was reduced and leak stopped. According to eye witnesses, between 5 and 10 gallons of liquid HCL coalesced and ran out of the rain drains from the spill dam onto pavement in the loading area. Cause of valve failure: Packing nuts and washers on the underside ot four of the six stainless steel 3/8' bolts holding the valve together in compression failed over time due to corrosion from the HCL. The nuts and washers were found n the spill dam during maintenance after the incident. Because of their orientation and proximity to the top of the tank, visual inspection is impossible without mirrors. Mitigation of future events: 1.) Replace bolts quarterly, and 2.) Utilize mirrors and lamps to inspect underside of all stainless bolts on closures and valves.
column169: Tank trailers in HCL service will be inspected in-house quarterly. The 3/8" bolts used to secure the assembly of the loading and/or unloading valves will be changed at this period. Use of a flashlight and mirror will be incorporated into quarterly inspections to observe underside of bolt and nut assemblies used on closure devices and valves.

column168: At approximately 0230 on October 11, 2011, a Terminal Railway switch crew discovered tank car NATX 71882 leaking product from the bottom steam outlet. The tank car was located in Track T-20 in the Terminal Railway Interchange Yard. Trainmaster John Milton took the necessary protective measures by establishing a safe perimeter and advising all Terminal personnel, including Manager Rules & Safety Paul Ashcraft, of the situation while Yardmaster Jason Jones contacted Chemtrec to address the leak and the accumulated product on the track. Trainmaster Milton also contacted Rayonier who was the shipper of this car for the MSDS sheet for the product. After reviewing the MSDS, Manager Rules & Safety Paul Ashcraft reapplied the cap on the steam valve outlet to stop the leak at approximately 0600.    Manager Rules & Safety Paul Ashcraft contacted ARC Terminals account the car had been released by ARC and pulled by Terminal Railway at approximately 2000 on October 10th to advise that the tank car was leaking and requested assistance in securing the car. Also, Mr. Ashcraft contacted Manager of Environmental Management for the Alabama State Port Authority for his assistance.    Rayonier who was the original shipper contacted United States Environmental Services to arrange for the remedial clean up of the contaminated area. It was estimated by  United States Environmental Services that approximately 30 to 40 gallons of product was released. It was determined that a cross threaded cap allowed the product to leak from this tank car.     United States Environmental Services completed the removal of all contaminated soil and ballast at approximately 1930 on October 11, 2011. The site was inspected by Manager of Environmental Management for the Alabama State Port Authority Cliff Wright
column169: ARC Terminals management has been advised to take measures to assure that all tank cars, loaded or empty, must be properly secured and fit for rail movement before being released for pull from their facility.

On 10/02/2011 at 0846 hours personnel at the CSXT Rice yard in Waycross, GA discovered GLNX 34589, a loaded tank car of Ammonia, Anhydrous Ammonia Liquefied, leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper Transammonia, State of Georgia DNR-EPD report #66551, NRC report #991439 and Chemtrec report #2011-10-02-00011, were notified. SWS, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the A end Liquid line valve 1/8 of a turn open and the secondary plug less than tool tight. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper's representative, Kimberly Desouza 813-261-0660. SWS personnel Secured the A end liquid valve and plug, securing and stopping the release and the car was released for transport.     This incident did require a special switching move.  A QA 7.1 Non conformance report is not required for this incident.    Cause Code:119  NARRI:5 (5+9+2) X (2+0) =160
column169: CSX Hazardous Materials Manager Chris Machenberg visited the company that loaded the rail car Mississippi Phosphates in Pascagoula Mississippi to discus the findings of the response contractor. Mississippi Phosphates will now remove all of the secondary securement plugs on all of the valves to insure there are no leaks and that all plugs are resecured properly. Previous procedure was to only remove the one liquid line valve plug that was being used and the one vapor line plug that was being used.

column168: On 10/62011 at 13:46 personnel at CSXT Parsons yard in Columbus, OH were informed by FRA inspector that UTLX 12117, a loaded tank car of Phosphoric Acid, was leaking from the vacuum relief device. The car was isolated and the shipper, PCS Sales, was notified via CHEMTREC Report 2011-10-06-00196. SWS Environmental, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and inspected the tank car. The vacuum relief device was verified to be worn and in need of a replacement. The PCS Sales representative, was informed of this issue and they arranged for delivery of a new replacement vacuum relief device. The replacement vacuum relief device was installed on October 11, 2011. The tank car is currently awaiting a requalifying bubble test to be performed prior to release for transportation.    This incident did require a special switching move.  A QA 7.1 Non Conformance Report is not required for this incident.    Cause Code: 461  5 x(5+3+0) x (2+0) = 80

On 10/12/2011 at 1211 hours personnel in the CSXT Montgomery Terminal discovered   UTLX 950687, a loaded tank car of Ammonia, Anhydrous, leaking from the pressure relief device. The car was isolated and the shipper PCS Sales, Alabama EMA and NRC, were notified - CHEMTREC report 2011-10-12-00143. United States Environmental Services (USES), a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found a slight leak coming from the o-ring cap of the pressure relief device. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper's representative,  personnel replaced the o-rings and the retainer cap, securing and stopping the vapor leak. The leak was secured and the car released for transport.    This incident did require a special switching move.   A QA 7.1 Non conformance report will be required. The container was secured and was sent for disposal to the intended waste management facility. All required local and state reports were made that included verbal reports to the Connecticut Department of Environmental Protection and local Fire Department.
column169: At the time the driver accepted the container for transportation, no evidence of leaking was observed. The driver, however, was re-instructed to conduct a  thorough inspection of each container before acceptance and if any evidence of a reduction in structural integrity is found to take appropriate action to either place the container into a suitable salvage drum or re containerize before transportation is initiated. In addition, the shipper was advised of the  incident and was requested to inspect all drums in current inventory for any containers with suspect integrity.

column168: The driver arrived at the customer’s site at 1230 to perform the transfer of product from an intermediate bulk container (IBC) to the customer’s tank. He connected a 2" chemical hose to the valve of the IBC that was to be transferred to the unloading pump. (2) 2" chemical hoses were then connected to the outlet of the unloading pump to the customer tank. The employee then secured all connections with Velcro straps. The customer informed the driver the unloading process was approved which he then engaged the air to the offloading pump and opened the IBC valve. The employee inspected all connections for any leaks. He noticed the product had developed a leak at the valve and hose connection. The driver then closed the valves to the IBC and pump to stop the transfer process. He then proceeded to clean up the spilled material; all recovered material was containerized for subsequent disposal. The driver inspected the chemical hose and found the gasket to be compressed. A new gasket was inserted into the hose connection and the transfer process resumed. Once the driver had returned to the shipping facility the gasket was inspected and confirmed his findings of being compressed.
column169: To prevent future incidents all employees who perform bulk unloading processes were instructed to change hose gaskets every 2 weeks. This was a monthly task prior to this incident. Drivers will again be instructed to inspect all hose gaskets prior to any bulk unloading and replace if the visual inspection of the gasket shows signs of damage or any compromises. This incident will also be reviewed by the safety committee, and in the monthly facility safety meeting.

column58: Manway or Dome Cover; Vacuum Relief Valve
column168: A FRA Railroad Safety Inspector (Hazardous Material) inspecting rail cars in the railyard, reported tank car CHVX 287226 with fresh product on and around its manway nozzle. No ground impact from spillage was reported. The FRA inspector reported one manway securement bolt adjacent to the manway cover hinge was not tool tight (hand tight only). Also, the vapor valve's closure plug was found not tool tight (hand tight only), with no reported leak from this orifice. CHVX 287226 was carefully moved and isolated in the railyard awaiting securement correction and spill remediation from a response contractor.  On 10/13/2011, inspection of CHVX 287226 by contract responders revealed that the two manway securement bolts positioned on either side of the manway cover hinge were not tool tight. The manway gasket was inspected and found serviceable. The manway cover was then closed and properly secured. A small dried product stain emanating at the vacuum relief valve's (VRV) threaded connection atop the manway cover near the hinge area was also observed. The VRV was removed and thread sealant applied to all threads. The VRV was reinserted and tool tightened. The vapor valve's closure plug that was not tool tight was removed. Thread sealant was applied to the plug's threaded connection; plug reinserted and tool tightened. Product stains on the tank shell were wiped and cleaned.   Intact manway cover seal CPC 215739 was replaced by seal TIS 5829.  Intact valve housing cover seal CPC 215741 was replaced by seal TIS 5827.  Response was concluded by 1100 hrs. MDT, 10/13/2011.  CHVX 287226's side specification stencil indicated that the last tank qualification was completed in the year 2002 and next due in 2012.

This shipment originated at Grand Rapids, Ml, and was transported via UPS Freight ground to the UPS facility in Chicago, where it was transferred to another UPS Freight ground vehicle for transport to Louisville (SDF). At Louisville, it was placed on a non-UPS vehicle (Covenant Transport) for further ground transport to the UPS facility at Dallas, TX for forwarding on to Los Angeles where it would then travel via air to final a destination of Kihei, HI. Origin Notes: The shipment was routed via truck from GRR to HCI, truck bill # T87GRR273001 (UPS Freight); from HCI to SDF (HWP), truck bill # T87HCI273017 (UPS Freight); & from SDF (HWP) to HTX, truck bill # T87HWP274020 (Covenant Transport).UPS" HTX discovered there were two sealed batteries, still connected, in the shipment during are build of the pallet this shipment was on. The item with the batteries is described as a "Treadmill Workstation Table".There were no markings, labels, or other shipping documents that would indicate this shipment contained batteries. Additional Contact at GRR: Ken Wiersma, 616-575-6914 - UPS SCS - Grand Rapids, Ml.

column168: On 10/13/11 at 0926 hours, personnel in the CSXT Hawthorne yard discovered SRIX 30202, a loaded tank car of Petroleum Distillates, N.O.S., with a splash leak from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Heritage Crystal Clean, was notified via CHEMTREC report 2011-10-13-00084. Summit Environmental, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found 3 of the 6 manway swing bolts not employed and the bottom outlet valve handle locking pin not installed. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper's representative.Environmental personnel replaced the manway gasket, secured the manway bolts, installed the lock with a security seals and decontaminated the car. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport.     This incident did require a special switching move.  A QA 7.1 Non conformance report is not required for this incident.    NARRI: 5 (5+1+0) x (2+0)= 60  Cause codes: 100; 200; and 208

column168: SUPERVISOR OF THE YELLOW WALL NOTICED A PUDDLE FORMING FROM UNDER A STACK OF IRREG PACKAGES BETWEEN DOORS 152 & 153.  HE ALSO NOTICED THE PACKAGE LEAKING WAS A HAZMAT.  HE IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED THE DESIGNATED RESPONDERS OF THE LEAKING HAZMAT.  WHEN I ARRIVED TO THE AREA, I USED MY DECISION TREE/RESPONSE SHEETS TO ASSESS THE SITUATION.  THE LEAKING PACKAGE WAS CORROSIVE.  ALTERED PPE TO INCLUDE THE SILVER SHIELD INNER LINERS BEFORE CLEANUP.  MOVED THE IRREG PACKAGES THAT HAD BEEN CRUSHING THE HAZMAT PACKAGE.  PUT ANY CONTAMINATED PACKAGES ON A CART.  CONTAINERIZED THE LEAKING PACKAGE INTO A LINED SPILL TRAY.  NEUTRALIZED ALL LIQUID WITH SODIUM BICARBONATE UNTIL THE PH WAS WITH IN THE 6-9 RANGE, THEN USED CLAY-BASED ABSORBANT TO SOLIDIFY ANY REMAINING LIQUIDS.  SWEPT THE AREA CLEAN OF THE SODIUM BICARB/ABSORBANT MIXTURE & PUT IT INTO ANOTHER LINED SPILL TRAY.  THEN TOOK THE PACKAGE TO THE DMP AREA FOR FURTHER PROCESSING.  1 OF THE 2500-ML BOTTLES HAD SHATTERED & SOILED THE OTHER 5.
column169: PRODUCT WAS PACKED WELL IN MOLDED STYROFOAM, BUT POSSIBLY THICKER STYROFOAM COULD HAVE BEEN USED.

On October 4, 2011, a Key Energy tractor tanker carrying Hydrochloric Acid released approximately 50 gallons of material onto the asphalt roadway and soil ditch along the roadway. The material sloshed out of the tanker during transportation. No storm drains or waterways were impacted as a result of this release. Key Energy Services personnel initially applied soda ash to the impacted asphalt roadway to contain the release. ERTS dispatched SWS to manage the release and perform cleanup operations. SWS personnel applied additional soda ash to the impacted asphalt and soil ditch line. All of the waste was collected and containerized for disposal. The impacted soil was hand excavated and graded back to original condition. No storm drains or waterways were impacted as a result of this release.

column168: On 10/6/11, at approx 1800 hours, while traveling west on Interstate 10,between mile marker 344 and 340,  Mr. Leroy Davenport, a driver for Safeway Transportation noticed that his engine light came on showing "stop engine"  and a water temperature of 250 degrees.  He put his four way flashers on, and proceeded towards the shoulder of I-10 to get off of the intestate highway.  He was halfway off the shoulder and coming to a complete stop when a tractor trailer hit him in the rear of the tanker trailer he was pulling. The tractor hit him with such force that it lifted the loaded trailer off of the ground, punctured the rear of the tank, and caused the spillage of the entire cargo from the tanker.  Safeway Transportation's trailer, and MC 407, was carrying 45,200 pounds of formaldehyde, solution, class 8; UN 2209: PG III, RQ.  The collisions resulted in a puncture to the rear of the trailer.  The force was so great that it ripped the fifth wheel off of the Safeway truck.  A small amount of Sodium Hydroxide solution was spilled by the van that hit the Safeway trailer.  The Sodium Hydroxide was being carried in a van trailer in totes, by Transport America, the owner of the other tractor trailer.    Emergency vehicles were dispatched from the local area.  A small fire truck arrived on the scene and assisted with the injured, and made themselves available to provided water support, if needed.  State Police arrived on the scene.   The leak was significant, and could not be stopped according to personnel at the scene.  Personnel were kept away from the trailer because of the product's  hazardous   nature.       A passenger in the Transport America truck was injured, and was trapped in her   seat. It took approx two hours to eventually free her and get her on a flight to the nearest hospital in Phoenix, Arizona.  Her injuries were not fatal.    The State Police and a hazmat team from the state of Arizona took command of the site, contacted Safeway Transportation, Inc., and maintained contact as needed throughout the evening, on into the next day. The State Police established a posture that would protect personnel and property in the area, and minimize exposure the environment.   This included the movement of sand to the contaminated area to avoid the odor as well as any run off.  The Haz Mat Officer and the Contractor coordinated this aspect of the operation.  All personnel working on the damaged trailer and product, donned their protective masks, and the area was cordoned off. Local and state police redirected traffic along the I-10 corridor, and shut down the flow of traffic as needed.   The police used cross over areas to facilitate the flow of traffic where they could.  The traffic shut down was said to be approximately 12 hours.  It was suggested by the Haz. Mat. Officer when he arrived on the scene that due  to the location of the incident and the time required to get a hazmat team out to this rural area in Arizona a contract hazmat team selected by
column169: SINCE THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A VEHICLE ACCIDENT THAT WAS THE RESULT OF SAFEWAY'S VEHICLE BEING STRUCK FROM BEHIND WE CANNOT THINK OF ANYTHING THAT THE SAFEWAY ORGANIZATION COULD HAVE DONE TO AVOID THIS ACCIDENT.  ON THE OTHER HAND, WE HAVE BEEN TOLD THAT THE VEHICLE THAT HIT SAFEWAY FROM BEHIND HAD AS MANY AS SIX DOGS IN THE CAB WITH HIS WIFE AND HIMSELF, WE WOULD SUGGEST THAT THE DOGS MAY HAVE BEEN A FACTOR. ALSO, SPEED AND FAILURE TO MAINTAIN CONTROL OF THE VEHICLE WERE FACTORS THAT CANNOT BE IGNORED.

The first spill was discoved leaking on 10/24/2011 at approximately 0845 in the cargo warehouse.  All packages surrounding the shipment were checked for contamination and moved away from the effected area.  The area was secured and spill containment material was laid on the area to surround pallet where the leak had been found.  Continental Airlines' Environmental Affairs department was called to clean the spill and dispose of the materials.      When the package was opened, it was found to be intact (on the inside and out); however, the paint on the inner drum was "bubbling" and material as leaking from the bottom seam of the drum.   There was no cushioning or absorbent material inside the package.  All 5 liters had been released.    It is unclear as to how long the package had been leaking, but was in an area that  would have been noticed if it had been leaking for a long period of time.    The second spill of the 2pc shipment was found at approximately 0630 on 10/26/2011 during a routine inventory check.  This piece had been removed from the pallet from the first spill to avoid contamination.  It had been checked and was not leaking on 10/24/2011.    Continental's Environmental Affairs department was called as well as local FAA Inspector Bob Craig.  Upon opening the second package, it was also determined that it had not been damaged, but was leaking from the bottom seam.  The paint on the innner package was also "bubbling" around the bottom seam.    The spill on the 2nd piece was approximately 1 liter of a total of 5 liters.
Operator began unloading tandwagon inside,  and did not verify that outdoor unload line was closed.

column168: An Ag Partners employee was returning NH3 nurse tanks (2-1000 gal. tanks) from a farmer’s field to Alta.   Apparently, the employee hooked up the safety chains and failed to put in a hitch pin.  On the way back to town, there was a downhill slope and the trailers started to sway back and forth.  Before the employee could get the pickup and trailers stopped, the safety chains broke and the two NH3 nurse tanks rolled into the ditch.  As a result of the tanks rolling, the rear tank twisted and broke off the hitch to the first tank and when it rolled the roll cage for the valves was broken away from the tank and the front liquid withdrawal valve was snapped off at the tank.  The excess-flow part of the valve remained in the tank and was only letting vapor escape from the tank. While efforts to put the nurse tanks in an upright position, there was a small amount of liquid that was stirred up and released into the air.  There was approximately 3-4% in the 1000 gallon nurse tank which equates to approximately 127#--176#.  There was no amount of Anhydrous released from the first tank.
column169: Ag Partners has retrained those employees that are involved with delivery and return of Anhydrous Ammonia Nurse tanks for farmer customers. This training consisted of discussion on the incident, only drivers with proper licensing & endorsements are to pull nurse tanks, procedures for hooking up nurse tanks to pickups, utilizing secondary gravel roads as much as possible to avoid traffic, speed while on the roads, stopping at all railroad crossings, lighting requirements, and paperwork required in pickups.

At 0130 I received a call from dispatch regarding and accident involving Aurelio  Saldivar at the intersection of Imperial and Atlantic. I immediately called Aurelio to make sure he was not injured. He stated he had already called 911 and he was not injured.    Driver stated he was making a left turn onto Imperial from Atlantic and tried to beat the light and took the turn too fast. The movement of the product caused the rear trailer to overturn. The trailer impacted a power poll forcing open the dome lid.    I then call John Miller and got him rolling to the accident, contacted Mo from Patriot and he was already in route. Brian had contacted him. I also notified Dave Palmer and had he started heading down. Around 0145 I called Aurelio again to see who had arrived and he stated LA Fire and the Sheriff Department was on scene. LA Fire was working on containing the product.    Around 0200 LA Fire Chief Ray called me to ask who our Hazmat Response Company was and the ETA. I told him Patriot Environmental and they should arrive in the next 15 to 30 min. Patriot arrived and the initial report of the spill was reported.    Around 0230 Miller arrived with a pump truck and reported the pull trailer was turned on its side and product was leaking out the dome lid. Our estimate was that 1500 gallons was released based on the remaining product that was pumped off. His plan was to pump off the trailer and have the towing service upright the unit. This was completed successfully and the truck and trailer was removed and taken to the Southgate yard around 0420.    Patriot started working on the clean up process. Dave arrived at 0510 and started communicating with the first responders. His report will contain all the contact information and any paperwork received. Final clean up was completed around 1500 and declared clear at this time.    A company safety meeting was held, details of the accident were discussed. Root causes was identified and discussed. Mandatory training on Roll over Prevention Video will be added to our training requirements.

Tote was loaded the night before delivery date without incident.  Driver inspected load during pre-trip inspection.  He did not note any leakage in truck and did not smell anything out of the ordinary.  When he arrived at his first stop, he noticed a smell and then saw the dampness on the floor of the trailer.  He then noted a 2' crack in the top of the tote tank.  The driver informed the carrier/shipment of the damage.  The product in the tote was then transferred to an undamaged container.   The tote was marked as defective and brought back to the shipper facility for evaluation.
column169: We are unable to determine the cause of the crack.  The tote was secured from both back-and-forth and lateral movement.  The tote was last tested in 10/11 so it was well within the test date.  Vibration during transporation may have been the cause of the damage.  We will review the incident with our employees and remind them about proper pre-filling inspections.

column168: NARRATIVE:   On October 13th at 11:45am, a rail to truck ethanol transfer was being conducted.  This was a four compartment trailer and the first compartment had been completed.  The second compartment was to receive 2000 gallons. Loader made all necessary connections and then set the pump pre-set meter for 2000 gallons. He started the transfer and periodically observed the meter for gallons pumped.  He first observed 1000 gallons had been transferred then looked back, and noticed the meter was stuck on 1600 gallons.  As he reached to shut down the transfer, he noticed compartment # 2 had overfilled.  Approximately 5 gallons of ethanol was retained in the drip pan and an additional 5 gallons overflowed the drip pan and contacted the ground. No drains or water was affected.    AWARENESS ITEMS:  1. The scully switch cover was closed and locked and keys were controlled by management.  Always ensure the pump is not in bypass mode prior to locking the cover.    2. Pump had a history of mechanical failure with its last repair being to the volume meter on 9/20/11.  This was the second transfer after the repair.    3. The scully is a protective system put in place to ensure trailers are not overloaded.  When operated in bypass mode, we work without any backup protective system.   4. Scully lights were tested and were proper working order: green-good ground; red- no ground; no lights if in bypass.   5. Floater employee was familiar with ethanol operation.
column169: ROOT CAUSES:  1. Equipment failure.  It was determined by an outside mechanic that the meter box was not functioning properly.   RBT made the recommendation to have the preset meter, temperature compensator and volume meter replaced.   2. The pump was being operated while in bypass mode.      CORRECTIVE ACTIONS:    1. Pump was immediately locked out and taken out of service.   2. The inspection of all scully switches will be made part of the monthly inspection to ensure they are not in bypass mode.   This is to be documented on the inspection sheet.

Savannah driver was South bound on I-35 a vehicle ahead of him missed the turn off to a center median rest stop and pulled to the right shoulder Savannah moved to the left lane to allow more room when the vehicle on the shoulder suddenly cut across two lanes pulled in front of Savannah in an effort to enter the rest area through the exit only lane of the rest area. Savannah tied to stop but hit the vehicle broad side and the Haz-Mat load shifted forward under the impact causing damage to the load. Kansas patrol responded as did the McPherson fire department, containers were crushed and dented but not leaking. The load was repositioned some drums over packed and shipment proceeded to final disposal facilities.
column169: This was a traffic accident which was unavoidable on the part of Savannah....other driver was cited.....the load and packaging with stood a huge impact without failure...amazing really!

REFERED TO DECISION TREE WHICH LED TO THE FLAMMABLE LIQUID RESPONSE SHEET.  THE FIRST PKG WAS CORROSIVE, INTACT, THAT HAD BEEN LEAKED ON BY THE FLAMMABLE LIQUID (METHANOL). PLACED ALL 4 PKGS IN SPILL TOTES, CLEANED THE FLOOR WITH CLAY ABSORBANT AND TOOK EVERYTHING TO DAMAGE REWRAP FOR PROCESSING.  ALL THAT WAS AFFECTED WITH PKGS 1,2,3 WAS THE CARDBOARD WHICH I CUT UP AND PLACED IN A GREEN BAG TO BE DMP'D.  USED SALVAGE DRUMS TO RETURN THE UNDAMAGED PRODUCT.  IN THE 4TH BOX ALL 4 BTLS NEEDED TO BE DMP'D BECASUE 1 SHATTERED AND THE OTHER THREE WERE CONTAMINATED BY THE ONE THAT HAD SHATTERED.  FOLLOWING THE RESPONSE SHEET FOR FLAMMABLE LIQUID, I DMP'D THE ENTIRE CONTENTS OF BOX 4.

On October 21, 2011 at approximately 12:06 PM, an Eastern Bulk Transportation truck  had started loading Methanol when the IMTT Operator discovered methanol dripping from the bottom of the trailer.  The IMTT Operator immediately placed a 5-gallon pail under the trailer to collect the dripping Methanol and notified his supervisor.  The Eastern Bulk Truck was secured and moved to an area with secondary containment and then contents transferred to another truck which was dispatched to the area.  The transfer was completed without incident and the eastern Bulk truck was released from the IMTT Terminal.

Transfer hydrochloric acid from IBC to bulk tank.  Driver connected hose form IBC to inlet side of transfer pump.  Driver connected hose to outlet side of transfer pump with transfer hose.  Driver then connected transfer hose from outlet side of transfer pump to consignee product line.  Consignee verified that the correct product line was connected.  Consignee verified by looking at automatic valve indicator that the valve was open and the product was ready for transfer.  Driver started transfer process and immediately noticed that the pump was laboring due to possible resistance of a shut valve or other restriction and shut down pump.  Driver again asked consignee if all valves were open.  The consignee verified again that the valve was open by looking at the indicator on the valve and calling their control room.  Driver started the transfer process again and the transfer line started to leak.  Driver shut down the process again.  Driver and consignee employees cleaned up the spilled material without issues or injuries.  Approximately 2 gallons of product was spilled into a containment area.  The transfer hose was noted to have a 1” crack approximately in the middle of the hose.
column169: Consignee discovered a blockage of their product line.  Consignee stated that they had removed the blockage from the line.

column168: On October 24, 2011 at approximately 5:30 PM, an Eastern Bulk Transportation truck had completed receiving a load of Methanol when an IMTT Operator discovered methanol dripping from the bottom of the trailer.  IMTT Operator immediately placed a 5-gallon pail under the trailer to collect the dripping Methanol and notified his supervisor. column168: THE RELEASE OF THIS MATERIAL WAS INCIDENTAL TO A TRAFFIC ACCIDENT AND RESULTING FIRE. A UPS TRACTOR-TRAILER DRIVER WITH A DOUBLE SET OF TRAILERS WAS PROCEEDING NORTH IN THE RIGHT LANE OF THE NJ TURNPIKE SERVICE ROAD BETWEEN EXITS 8A AND 9. HE WAS FORCED TO BRAKE SUDDENLY TO AVOID STRIKING ANOTHER TRACTOR-TRAILER, WHICH CUT OFF HIS VEHICLE. THE UPS VEHICLE JACKKNIFED, CAUSING THE TRACTOR AND FIRST TRAILER TO MOVE INTO THE LEFT LANE, WHERE IT WAS STRUCK BY A DIESEL FUEL TANKER. OF THE OVER 4,000 PACKAGES AND LETTERS CONTAINED IN THE TWO TRAILERS, THREE PACKAGES CONTAINED HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, AND THIS ONE CONTAINING UN3266 WAS INVOLVED IN THE RESULTING FIRE. THE OTHER TWO UNDAMAGED HAZARDOUS MATERIALS PACKAGES WERE RECOVERED AND SUBSEQUENTLY DELIVERED.

column168: On October 10, 2011 at approximately 1730, a company transport was loaded and traveling on 121 Rd (dirt/mud) North of Kingsdown, KS.  While maneuvering through an "S" curve, the driver drove the tractor too far into the left shoulder where it was very  muddy. The driver attempted to bring the tractor back onto solid ground and did so too abrubtly.  This inappropriate reaction caused the weight of the loaded trailer to carry the tractor-trailer over on its left side.  The tractor-trailer came to rest on the left side shoulder of the road.  The driver exited the cab and notified his Supervisor.  Kansas Highway Patrol responded to the scene as well as company personnel. No product was spilled.  Due to muddy conditions and darkness, the KS Highway patrol made the decision to secure the scene and postponed uprighting the truck until morning.  The following morning, the product was transferred to another transport.  The wrecked transport was then uprighted and towed away by wrecker service.  No further action was required, and no clean up was necessary.
column169: The root cause of this lay-over accident was due to the driver's mistake in driving too far onto the muddy shoulder of the road and subsequently reacting to the situation inappropriately.  The vehicle's estimated speed just before the lay-over was 25 mph.  The driver could have avoided the shoulder all together as there was enough room to navigate the transport around the curve safely.  The driver could have also responded differently once he realized he was too deep into the shoulder.  He could have easily continued forward and come to rest instead of aggressively attempting to bring the tractor back onto solid ground.  Additional awareness training on the factors that caused this accident is warranted.  All company drivers will participate in an accident review process to include discussion on what went wrong and how to avoid the situation in the future.

NORMAL PROCEDURE IS TO ARRIVE AT STATION, MAKE SURE ONE IS AT THE CORRECT STATION, OBTAIN A VEETER ROOT, STICK THE UNDERGROUND TANKS, GO BY THE TANK CHART AND DO THE MATH TO MAKE1 SURE THE PRODUCT WILL HOLD. column168: On October 19, 2011, R&L Carriers contacted ERTS to manage a leaking 275 gallon poly tote of UN1993 Xylene Solvent Flammable Liquid. ERTS dispatched B&P Enterprise to the site to investigate the release and perform cleanup operations. B&P Enterprise personnel reported that cargo was placed on top of the tote, which caused it to bend and ultimately resulted in a hole in the tote. B&P Enterprise personnel reported that approximately 5 gallons of material released onto the trailer floor and also impacted a small area of the asphalt parking lot. B&P Enterprise personnel initially plugged the leaking tote until a transfer could be made. B&P Enterprise personnel utilized absorbents to collect the released material from the impacted trailer floor and asphalt parking lot. B&P Enterprise personnel transferred the material from the damaged tote into a replacement tote. All of the waste along with the damaged tote was collected and containerized for transportation and disposal. No storm drains, waterways or soils were impacted as a result of this release.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While making delivery, a leak was discovered coming from the trailer.   Free product released to the asphalt parking lot beneath trailer.  Area was isolated and regulatory agencies were notified.  Best Environmental Services of Chesterfield, Indiana was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  Upon inspection of the trailer, one (1) 55-gallon drum was discovered leaking.  Approximately 15 gallons of free product were released to the trailer floor and asphalt surface.  Best Environmental Services placed absorbent pads on the affected surface(s) and wiped contaminated freight.  The damaged drum was overpacked into one (1) 85-gallon overpack, which was left on site pending disposition.  The spent absorbents and cleanup materials were placed into one (1) 55-gallon recovery drum, pending disposal in accordance with local, state, and federal regulations.  The free liquid did not impact surface soils or threaten to impact waters of the state.  There were no injuries or exposures reported.
column169: Metropolitan Trucking will continue to train and reinforce safe handling procedures to all personnel.

Railcar GATX 32735 (R/ HYDROCHLORIC ACID SOLUTION) was observed venting during switching operations at the CN Destrehan Yard, LA.  The railcar was isolated and all appropriate departments notified.  CN's response team responded, upon closer inspection vapors were observed coming from under the fill hole cover.  The bolts securing the fill hole cover were checked for tightness. column168: On 10/29/2011 at 1405 hours,  a Selkirk yard car inspector noticed an odor near UTLX 207272, a loaded tank car of Alcohols, N.O.S. The tank car was isolated and the shipper, Flint Hills Resources, LLC, was notified via CHEMTREC report   2011-10-29-00081. EP+S of Vermont (EP+S VT), a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to investigate and found the pressure relief device (PRD) re closing valve defective - valve center shaft was broken and able to be lifted. The car was move to an isolation track and Alltranstek, LLC, agent for Flint Hills Resources, LLC, was contacted and advised of the broken PRD. CSXT was notified by Jack Crook, Rescar Industries, on 11/2/2011 that they will replaced the PRD on 11/9/2011 and performed a qualification test.      This incident did require a special switching move.  A QA 7.1 Non conformance report is required for this incident.    Cause Code: 418  NARRI: 2 (5+3+0) x (2+0) = 32

column168: On October 25, 2011 at approximately 1700 hours tank car GATX 73710 was observed leaking from the 2" liquid line while PTRA crews were switching the car at the North Yard. Investigation found that the valve had two of four flange bolts missing. Solvay chemicals was notified and they indicated two of the flange bolts were striped and the car was undergoing repairs when it was mistakenly placed into the outbound track for pick up by the PTRA. PTRA crews pulled the car on 10/20/2011 at 1200 hours and the car was taken to PTRA North Yard. On 10/25 M&M Protection as well as representatives from Solvay arrived at north yard to inspect the car. Product on the side of the car was remediated. Approximately one gallon of product was released. M&M made temporary repairs so the car could be moved to the RIP tracks in North Yard. On 10/26 M&M and Solvay repaired the stripped bolts and secured the car for movement back to Solvay to be unloaded.

GATX 18024 was noted by carrier personnel with tank shell collapsed or imploded on arrival inspection at Sharonville Yard.  Car isolated and shipper notified.      Shipper representatives, SWS Environmental, responded and found a 10 inch long by 1 inch wide crack at the base of the manway nozzle flange due to the collapse of the tank shell.  Preliminary investigation developed that the material was loaded at an elevated temperature and the car is non-insulated and is not equipped with a vacuum relief valve to allow for cooling and contracting of the contents en route.  It is suspected the negative pressure inside the tank shell caused the shell to implode during transportation releasing a small amount of material from the 10 inch crack.      The crack was located at the highest point on the car after the defect developed.  The remaining product was transferred into six trucks and returned to shipper's origin facility for further handling.  Scale weights of the inbound trucks indicated little to know actual product loss.    The car will be cleaned and scrapped on site.          Photos attached.

column168: TANKER WAS N/B ON HWY 101 IN FOGGY CONDITIONS WITH 500'+ VISIBILITY AT ABOUT 51 MILES PER HOUR (PER GPS). THIS AREA OF HWY IS CURRENTLY UNDER CONSTRUCTION WITH UNEVEN PAVEMENT AND K RAIL BARRIERS FROM TIME TO TIME. DRIVER WAS MOVING IN THE FLOW OF TRAFFIC AND FAILED TO NOTICE TRAFFIC SLOW AND COME TO A STOP. WHEN HE NOTICED THAT TRAFFIC HAD STOPPED HE ATTEMPTED TO STOP AS WELL. DURING THIS PROCESS HE REALIZED THAT HE WAS NOT GOING TO BE ABLE TO STOP IN TIME TO PREVENT A COLLISION WITH THE REAR OF A TRUCK AHEAD OF HIM SO HE ATTEMPTED TO BYPASS THE TRUCK BY GOING INTO THE LANE TO HIS LEFT. IN DOING SO HE WAS NOT ABLE TO COMPLETELY CLEAR THE REAR OF THAT TRUCK STRIKING THE LEFT REAR CORNER OF THE FLATBED WITH THE HOSE TUBES ON THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE TRUCKS TANK. WHEN THIS HAPPENED THE HOSE TUBE COLLAPSED AND BROKE A MOUNTING BRACKET AND PUNCTURED THE TANK WITH ABOUT A TWO INCH GASH CAUSING PRODUCT TO SPILL ONTO THE ROADWAY AND THEN FLOW ONTO THE SHOULDER OF THE HWY. THE RESULT WAS A SPILL OF APPROXIMATELY 1918 GALLONS FROM A TANK HOLDING APPROXIMATELY 4000 GALLONS.

column168: Driver was headed westbound on I-84 exiting off at US89 southbound interchange near the mouth of Weber canyon.  Driver failed to negotiate curve for unknown reason, lost control, and rolled truck and semi trailer.  Pup trailer remained up. Driver was fatally injured when truck came in contact with jersey barrier.  UHP commented to me unofficially speed into the off ramp was the major contributing cause.  No other parties involved and no witnesses.  Inspection report found one brake out of adjustment, but nothing else.  Truck was loaded with butane coming from Opal, WY and unloading at the Big West refinery in North Salt Lake.  No release of product from either trailer.    We called Mountain States Propane to offload the butane.  Lincoln Environmental was called by the local fire department for possible hazmat cleanup and remediation.  A representative from Weber County Health Department was there to monitor Lincoln’s cleanup efforts.       UDOT provided barricades for road closures from approximately 11:30 until 5:30.  Associated Towing removed the trailers from the scene.  All butane was taken to the refinery and off-loaded.  Notification was made to the National Response Center; report number is 993702.
column169: This driver had recently gone through our rollover prevention training along with many others in our safety training program.  There was no reason that police or our investigation could find as to why he entered the offramp with excessive speed and unable to make the curve.  No breach of product occurred even with the overturn.    Only possible cause we could determine was some sort of driver distraction or medical condition.  We were not notified of any health concerns on the autopsy, nor was UHP able to determine any sort of driver distraction.

column168: Our truck was involved in an accident with another vehicle. The point of impact was at the rear axles at the back of the trailer. This impact was strong enough to open the bottom fill valve on the trailer ¼ turn. The valve would ordinarily not open very easily. The liquid nitrogen leaked from this valve for two hours which emptied the entire load. Liquid nitrogen boils and vaporizes at normal temperatures so the entire load returned to the atmosphere. The valve could have possibly been closed but the first responders did not want to approach the trailer.
column169: We had a discussion with the first responders on the scene about how to deal with a nitrogen release and the precautions to take. We are discouraging our drivers from using mountainous two lane roads when there is a safer alternative route. The route where the accident occurred has many curves and steep grades.  The trailer is a very sturdy design as is the valve that came open. The driver could have forgotten to tighten the valve enough but we have no way of knowing. Training for the drivers will stress checking trailer valves at each stop to make sure they are tight.

column168: A crate containing 51 helium gas cylinders (each containing 1.3 grams He-3 at 44 psia) was at the New York Container Terminal (NYCT) with other crates.  Because it was not intended that the crate would be loaded or shipped at that time, the crate was not marked or labeled for shipment and there was no associated shipping paper.  The crate was inadvertently loaded with other crates, which did not contain hazmat. It is not known who loaded the crate but it was likely a NYCT subcontractor.  The undeclared hazardous material shipment was discovered after receipt during conversation between the YRC warehouse staff in Grove City, OH (the receiving facility) and Pacific Northwest National Laboratory (Battelle) technical staff.  There were no releases or other incidents either in loading, transit or unloading.  This report is being submitted as required for an undeclared hazardous material, per 171.16(a)(4).
column169: Facility managers should implement hazardous material container marking/labeling controls consistent with OSHA requirement.  These marking/labeling should be sufficient to alert trained staff that hazardous materials are present and that hazmat transportation controls will be necessary when items are offered for shpiment.

column168: WE MADE DELIVERY OF #2 DYED OFF-ROAD FUEL OIL INTO A RIVER BARGE LOCATED AT THE KINDER MORGAN FACILITY. POST OUR DELIVERY, A KINDER MORGAN REPRESENTATIVE FELT HE OBSERVED A "SHEEN" OF SOMETHING AROUND OUR TANK WAGON DELIVERY UNIT; AND AS PER THEIR PROCEDURES THEY REPORTED AN INCIDENT TO NRC. REPONSE TO SITE WAS EFFECTED BY THE LOCAL COAST GUARD AS WELL AS A MANAGER OF OUR COMPANY. ALL PARTIES AGREED THAT THERE HAD BEEN NO SPILLAGE OF PRODUCT DURING THE OFF-LOADING PROCESS AND THAT THE SHEEN THAT THEY HAD OBSERVED WAS PRESUMED TO COME AS A "RUNOFF" FROM OUR UNIT - AS A HEAVY RAIN WAS FALLING DURING THE TIME OF OUR DELIVERY. PRESUMPTION IF THAT THE "SHEEN" WAS A RESULT OF POSSIBLE RUNOFF OF EITHER ROAD RESIDUALS OFF OF OUR UNIT OR POSSIBLY SOME PRODUCT RESIDUAL MAY HAVE DROPPED OFF OR BEEN RUN OFF BY RAIN FROM THE REAR ACCESS DOOR/PUMP SHELF AREA OF THE TANK WAGON UNIT AS OUR DRIVER HAD PLACED A FEW SOP PADS WITH OIL/GREASE RESIDUAL IN THE TRAY AREA. IT IS OUR UNDERSTANDING FROM A REPRESENTATIVE AT KINDER MORGAN THAT THEY DEPLOYED BOOMS INTO RIVER AS A PRECAUTIONARY MEASURE AND THAT NO DETECTIBLE MATTER WAS OBSERVED WHEN THE BOOMS WERE RETRIEVED; AND THAT WHAT RESIDUAL HAD BEEN INITIALLY PRESUMED NOTED BY THE KINDER MORGAN REPRESENTATIVE WAS NOT VISIBLE TO/WHEN THE COAST GUARD REPRESENTATIVE ARRIVED.
column169: IT HAS BEEN DECIDED TO MAKE DELIVERIES AT THE SITE DURING DRY WEATHER CONDITIONS IN THE FUTURE TO AVOID THE POSSIBLE ISSUED OF SUCH AS A HEAVY RAIN FALL CONTRIBUTING TO RESIDUAL RUNOFF FROM THE EXTERIOR OF THE VEHICLE THAT COULD BE POSSIBLY DETECTED AS A "SHEEN". INTERNALLY, WE HAVE INITIATED PROCEDURE THAT WE WILL HAVE A UNIT THAT IS DESIGNATED FOR DELIVERY TO THIS SITE, TO PULL THROUGH OUT SHOP AND HAVE A PRE-LOAD INSPECTION TO MAKE SURE THERE IS NO EVIDENCE OF ANY PETROLEUM PRODUCTS ON THE EXTERIOR SURFACES OF WITH THE CONFINES OF THE REAR ACCESS DOOR TO THE TANK WAGON VEHICLE. IT IS FURTHER NOTED THAT KINDER MORGAN WILL ALSO EFFECT A VISUAL INSPECTION OF ANY UNIT WE PRESENT TO OFFLOAD PRODUCT AT THEIR SITE IN THE FUTURE TO VERIFY THE OVERALL CLEANLINESS OF THE UNIT.

column42: RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL, EXCEPTED PACKAGE-LIMITED QUANTITY OF MATERIAL
column168: On October 27 at approximately 14:30 a "Radioactive material, excepted package-limited quantity of material" shipment arrived at Duke Energy Corporation ENRAD Laboratory located in Huntersville, N.C. from Duke Energy Corporation Oconee Nuclear Station (ONS) located in Seneca, SC.  The material was being transported by Murphy Courier Service Inc.  When ENRAD shipping and receiving personnel opened the doors of the closed vehicle they observed that the two wooden packages inside were damaged.  One had a 4-5 inch opening in the bottom where the floor of the box had separated from the upper walls of the box.  The other had a loose 2X4 board attached to the outside but was not breached.  ENRAD personnel immediately secured the area around the transport vehicle and began surveys of the packages and vehicle to determine if any radioactive contamination had been released.  Surveys results identified that no radioactive contamination had been released.  ENRAD personnel then determined and executed a process for removing the packages without causing further damage to the packages or release of radioactive contamination.  The packages were then properly stored according to ENRAD radiation protection procedures.  A gross contamination survey, using a treated cloth, along with a direct surface radiation readings survey were performed on the cargo area.  There was no contamination detected in the cargo area of the vehicle so the driver and the vehicle were released.  A Duke Energy Nuclear Generation Problem Investigation Program (PIP) event was written for the incident (G-11-1599).  The Oconee Radiation Protection Manager, Oconee Radiation Protection Shipping Supervisor, General Office Radioactive Shipping Support person, and General Office Radiation Protection Supervision were notified at approximately 18:49.    The reporting requirements of 49CFR171.15 were discussed with the General Office Radioactive Shipping Support person that evening.  In particular, the meaning of "breakage" as specified in 49CFR173.15(b)(3) was discussed.  It was decided to gather more information concerning the incident and confirm the meaning of "breakage" the next morning prior to contacting the DOT.  The morning of Oct. 28 the DOT Hotline was contacted concerning whether "breakage" meant breakage of the package.  The DOT Hotline promptly referred the General Office Radioactive Shipping Support person to PHMSA Interpretation #08-0213, December 18, 2008 which specified that notification of the DOT is required when the package is broken, regardless of whether the inner container is intact.  The DOT Response Center was contacted at 13:50. Courtesy calls were also made to the North Carolina radiation protection licensing area, US Nuclear Regulatory Commission, and to American Nuclear Insurers.    Problem with Package Construction:    Inspection was performed on the packages to determine the quality of the construction.  Both packages were constructed of wood with clean square cuts that
column169: Oconee Nuclear Station, McGuire Nuclear Station, and Catawba Nuclear Stations radioactive shipping areas were provide pictures of the damaged packages, information on the incident, and a warning about using wooden packages on 10/31/11.      System wide interim actions were implemented  11/2/2011 that required permission from the Radiation Protection Manager at each station's approval prior to using packaging made of wood.     The following are excerpts of changes that have been approved for inclusion in the standard shipping procedures for Oconee, McGuire, and Catawba Nuclear Stations.     IF during transport of radioactive material in commerce, as defined in 49CFR171.1, a DOT incident as noted in 49CFR171.15 or 49CFR171.16 occurs (e.g.; person injured or killed, traffic disrupted, fire, breakage of package even with no release of radioactive material, suspected contamination release, undeclared DOT hazardous material discovered); ensure the incident reporting requirements of 49CFR171.15, 49CFR171.16, 10CFR71.5, and ANI are satisfied by referring to References 2.16, 2.28, and 2.29     IF feasible, avoid use of packages constructed from wood when shipping heavy items.       Suggestions for packages constructed from wood:   - Items inside boxes shall be cradled or supported in a manner that avoids  concentration of weight on small areas of the floor of the box (e.g.; cradle or   reinforcing of specific areas of the floor to distribute weight).  Points and narrow edges shall be padded or prevented from coming in contact with the shell of the   package.     - Consideration shall be given to ensuring the weight of the material will not     damage the box shell when being lifted by forklifts/fork trucks.  Ensure cradles    and/or flooring are constructed in a manner that result in minimum flex in     flooring when supported by feet or forklift.    - Avoid construction that allows lifting of package using upper structures of box    (e.g.; rim attached to walls of box).  (It is difficult to attach the floor of a    wooden box to the upper structure in a manner that will prevent separation when lifting using the upper structure.)     -  Junction of walls, floor, and lid shall be inspected to ensure adequate nails or screws have been used to join the applicable components. Keep in mind that nails or screws driven between layers of laminated wood (ends) has less holding strength than nails or screws driven through the multiple layers.     IF using a packaging constructed from wood, Radiation Protection Manager approval required.

column168: Driver was headed west on I-70 through Topeka, KS with a load of asphalt oil (Class 9).  The driver hit a concrete barrier separating the interstate roadways and flipped over.  The driver was killed upon impact with the concrete barrier and signage.  The overturned tank began to leak asphalt oil.  The Topeka police called and notified me of the accident around 5:30 a.m. and asked what the content was in the trailer.  I immediately drove to the scene to assist with calling HazMat Response and answer any questions by emergency personnel.  The Fire Department contained the oil that was spilling by making a berm made of sand and dirt until the HazMat crew was allowed to begin cleanup. Cleanup occurred after the accident investigation team was complete which took at least five hours.  The oil was spilling from a rupture/crack that occurred during the roll-over near the rear discharge.  The Hazmat Response team was able to successfuly clean up all of the oil that was spilled.  A second tanker was called in to remove as much of the remaining oil as possible from the tank.
column169: I am still unclear as to why the driver hit the concrete barrier.  We have not received an official accident report or medical/coroner report as of yet.  The driver just began the shift of duty and was only 4 hours into shift and had the adequate rest period prior to beginning the shift.

column168: ON OCTOBER 3, 2011, MR. KETTMAN RECEIVED A CALL FROM CONWAY TRUCK LOAD REGARDING A TRACTOR/TRAILER UNIT THAT HAD CAUGHT FIRE ALONG I-81, MILE MARKER 80.0 IN GRANTVILLE, PA. THE INFORMATION PROVIDED INDICATED THE TRAILER HAD BEEN CARRYING A LOAD OF CAR BATTERIES. THE LOAD SOME HOW CAUGHT FIRE DURING TRANSIT. THE DRIVER PARKED THE TRACTOR/TRAILER ON THE SHOULDER OF THE ROAD. THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT HAD BEEN CALLED TO THE SITE TO EXTINGUISH THE FLAMES.  AS A RESULT OF THE FIRE, THE SHRINK WRAP SECURING THE BATTERIES TOGETHER ON THE PALLET MELTED.  THE HEAT FROM THE FIRE THEN CAUSED SEVERAL BATTERIES TO START MELTING WHICH RESULTED IN THE RELEASE OF THE BATTERY ACID.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT EXTINGUISHED THE FLAMES WITH SEVERAL GALLONS OF WATER.  THE WATER USED TO EXTINGUISH THE FLAMES MIXED WITH THE BATTERY ACID WHICH WAS CONTAINED TO THE ROADWAY AND THE SOIL ALONG SHOULDER OF I-80. AN ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANUP CREW HAD BEEN DISPATCHED TO THE SITE TO ASSIST IN THE CONTAINMENT OF THE BATTERY ACID AND THE NEUTRAILIZATION OF THE FIRE WATER MIXED WITH ACID.  IT IS UNDETERMINED HOW MANY GALLONS OF BATTERY ACID HAD BEEN RELEASED DUE TO THE FIRE.  UPON COMPLETION OF THE CLEANUP, THE ENTIRE LOAD OF BATTERIES WERE REMOVED FROM THE TRAILER AND SORTED.  THE ENVIRONMENTAL CREW REMOVED A TOTAL OF 13 PALLETS OF UNDAMAGED BATTERIES, 7 CUBIC YARD BOXES OF BATTERIES WHICH WERE DAMAGED IN VARIOUS WAYS, ONE CUBIC YARD BOX AND 13 DRUMS OF BROKEN MISCELLANEOUS BATTERY PIECES AND TWO 55 GALLON DRUMS OF POURED UP BATTERY ACID.
column169: A CLOSER LOOK AT THE PACKAGING OF THE BATTERIES AND THE INSTALLATION OF BATTERY TERMINAL COVERS WOULD REDUCE THE CHANCES OF A SPARK.

column168: A TRACTOR TRAILER WITH A LIFTGATE WAS PARKED ON THE STREET TO DELIVER TWO DRUMS OF TETRACHLOROETHYLENE TO A DRY CLEARNERS. THE STREET HAD MODERATE INCLINE WITH THE BACK OF THE TRAILER IN THE DOWN HILL DIRECTION. AFTER THE FIRST DRUM WAS UNLOADED, THE SECOND DRUM WAS BEING MOVER TO THE LIFTGATE AT THE REAR OF THE TRAILER WITH A DRUM DOLLY. THE DRIVER UNLOADING THE DRUM AS UNABLE TO STOP THE MOMENTUM OF THE MOVING DRUM IN TIME FOR IT TO REST ON THE LIFTGATE AND THE DRUM FELL FROM THE TRAILER ONTO THE STREET. THE FORCE OF THE FALL CAUSE THE TOP OF THE OPEN-HEAD DRUM TO COME OFF FROM WHICH THE SPILL OCCURRED.  THE RELEASED MATERIAL FLOWED TO THE CURB AND INTO A STORM DRAIN WHERE IT TRAVELED FOR APPROXIMATELY 200 FEET. THE DRIVER USED CLAY ABSORBENT TO ABSORB AND CONTAIN THE MATERIAL ON THE STREET AND CURB. THE DRIVER CALLED THE OFFICE AND A RESPONSE TEAM WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SITE TO CLEAN THE STORM DRAIN. THE STREET WAS PRESSURE WASHED AND THE AFFECTED PORTION OF THE STORM DRAIN WAS FLUSHED WITH WATER, CONTAINING ALL MATERIAL FOR DISPOSAL IN A VACUUM TRUCK.  AN ENVIRONMENTAL ASSESSMENT OF SPILL HAS BEEN PERFORMED AND NO REMEDIATION HAS BEEN REQUIRED. A 6-MONTH REPEAT SOIL SAMPLE AT ONE LOCATION ALONG THE STORM DRAIN IS REQUIRED BY JUNE 2012.

column168: The following is a narrative of the events surrounding the fuel release of our tanker truck unit #50,occurring on October 19th, 2010. This information is being provided for the purpose of documenting the activity, and to aid in the processing of the claim. DEC has expressed their satisfaction with our response, on more than one occasion during the cleanup.    Fuel release occurred on October 19th around 12:30pm we had the spill contained and all standing fuel, saw dust and absorbent pads/booms picked up and hauled out to OIT (Organic Incineration Technology) all before 7pm.    Day of the spill October 19th:  • Freezing rain and snow the evening before created exceptionally icy roads with ice and snow, as reported in the local paper.  • Driver had 4,300 gallons on the truck and took a corner too fast on Easy Street, and after sliding, the back tires hit the curb making the truck tip over on its side. The rear bulkhead separated,spilling fuel.  • An unidentified person came upon the scene and called 911, turned off the truck, and checked on our driver  • Fairbanks Fire,Police,DEC and rescue units showed up on the scene  • Fairbanks Police called Ben's Towing to see if they could upright the truck to stop the fuel  • Bob Wilson (GM for Aerofuel) was notified/Bob notified myself as he and our shop manager Randy Wilson left for the scene  • I responded to the scene and arrived the same time as Bob Wilson/Our insurance company was notified  • Randy called Alaska Rubber for the purchase of absorbent material.  They prepared securing the absorpent material, and we loaded our pickup along with a couple of their trucks to bring to the site.  • Randy called our shop, dispatching another truck to the site for pump out the remaining fuel from our truck  • Alaska Rubber and Alaska Aerofuel personnel distributed absorbent material to stop the spreading of fuel  • Rescue crews removed the windshield and part of the truck cab to extract the driver and transported him to the hospital  • Ben's Towing righted the truck on its wheels,causing the fuel to stop leaking/Ben's Towing removed the unitto our yard  • Randy sent one of our personnel to Northland Wood (nearby) to pick up plastic and ordered a dump truck load of saw dust (sawdust to absorb fuel, and plastic to line the trucks for hauling)  • Great North West was contacted for bringing a couple dump trucks, drivers and a loader to the site for spreading sawdust and transport to OIT.  • Fairbanks Pumping and Thawing was contacted for assistance (they have a vacuum truck which can be used for fuel).  • OIT was alerted, and we were informed all absorbents would need to be brought in drums.  • Arctic Fire and Safety was notified  and delivered 18 drums, rubber gloves and booties for everyone working with fuel at the site  • Fairbanks Fuel showed up and vacuumed all standing fuel, on and off the road  • All absorbents were picked up, drummed, and put in a lined dump truck to go to OIT  • Northland Wood showed up with

column168: Because there are no witnesses, we can only go by what was written on police report.  Unit 1 was towing Unit 2 northbound on FM 649 near MM656.  Unit 1 and Unit 2 came off the roadway on the east side.  Unit 1 over-corrected across the southbound lane onto loose dirt and attempted to re-enter roadway.  Unit 2 continued onto loose dirt causing Unit 1 and Unit 2 to roll to left side.  Unit 2 came to rest upright after a complete roll.  Driver was ejected from Unit 1 and pronounced dead at the scene.    The rollover caused for his trailer to release most of the fuel on the ground.  There was no phone signal and DPS only had our office phone numbers, 4 hours had passed by the time we were contacted.  DPS had already called the fire department and clean up crew.
column169: We have instructed our drivers to ONLY drive on certain roads. This was an unauthorized road to be on due to the fact that it had no shoulders and the drop from road to dirt is very uneven and about 5 inches down.  We met with all drivers and stressed the importance of wearing their seat belts.

column168: On 10/23/2011, product had shifted in a gondola during switching operations.  This caused the material to shift to the east end and out from under the cover onto the ground. The solid material was loaded with too much moisture content, allowing it to shift in transportation.  The released product was removed from the soil surface and placed back into the car . The load was shifted back to an appropriate profile, the top was secured and the car was released back into transportation.

column168: SEQUENCE OF EVENTS:  THE DRIVER LEFT THE INSPECTION STATION IN NORTH PLATTE, NE AND DROVE TO THE BOSSELEMAN TRUCKSTOP AT INTERSTATE 80, EXIT 312.  THE DRIVER EXITED THE TRUCK AND NOTICED LIQUID DRIPPING FROM THE FRONT PORTION OF THE TRAILER.     ACTIONS TAKEN:  THE DRIVER CALLED THE CARRIER (SMITH SYSTEMS TRANSPORTATION) AND REPORTED THE RELEASE.  THE DRIVER HAD ACCESS TO A BAG OF CLAY ABSORBENTS AND WAS ABLE TO PLACE THE ABSORBENTS ON THE RELEASED MATERIAL ON THE ASPHALT PARKING AREA TO PREVENT FURTEHR MIGRATION OF THE MATERIAL.  THE CARRIER CALLED ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT, INC., AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE COMPANY FOR THE CARRIER, AND ENVIRONMENTAL   MANAGEMENT DISPATCHED A LOCAL ENVIRONMENTAL COMPANY TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP ACTIVITIES.  THE TRAILER FLOOR WAS LOADED APPROXIMATELY 60% FULL WITH A SINGLE LAYER OF 55-GALLON DRUMS.  THE CLEANUP CREW ARRIVED ON-SITE AND UNLOADED THE TRAILER USING A MINI-EXCAVATOR AND A DRUM SLING.  THE CREW LOCATED THE LEAKING DRUM NEAR THE FRONT OF THE TRAILER AND INVERTED THE DRUM TO STOP THE LEAK.  A CRACK IN THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM, APPROXIMATELY 1 INCH LONG, WAS THE REASON FOR THE LEAKAGE.  THE CREW PLACED THE FAILED DRUM INTO AN 85-GALLON SALVAGE DRUM.  THE CREW THEN USED CLAY ABSORBENTS TO REMOVE THE RELEASED MATERIAL FROM THE TRAILER FLOOR AND FROM THE DRIVEWAY UNDER THE TRAILER.  THE CONTAMINATED ABSORBENTS WERE COLLECTED AND PLACED INTO AN 11-GALLON WASTE DRUM AND LABELED FOR DISPOSAL.  THE TRAILER WAS RELOADED, INCLUDING THE 85-GALLON SALVAGE DRUM AND THE 11-GALLON WASTE DRUM AND THE LOAD WAS SECURED.  THE TRUCK WAS THEN RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO THE DESTINATION.  THE WASTE FROM THE CLEANUP ACTIVITIES HAS BEEN SENT FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.                                                      PACKAGE FAILURE:  A 1" LONG CRACK IN THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM CAUSED A RELEASE OF THE DRUM'S CONTENTS.                                   CAUSE OF THE FAILURE:  THE CRACK APPEARED TO BE A STRESS FRACTURE CAUSED BY THE FLEXING OF THE STEEL DRUM BOTTOM DURING LOADING/UNLOADING AND TRANSPORTATION.  THE DRUM APPEARED TO HAVE BEEN AN OLD DRUM AND WAS POSSIBLY DAMAGED AT SOME POINT, PRIOR TO BEING LOADED ONTO THIS TRAILER, CAUSING A WEAK AREA WHERE THE CRACK OCCURRED.                          PHOTOGRAPH ATTACHED.
